## ASSISTANT
Short answer: within the usual axioms of set theory (ZFC), the Continuum Hypothesis (CH) can neither be proved nor disproved. In other words, CH is **independent** of ZFC (assuming ZFC is consistent).

| Item | Precise claim | Status in ZFC | What that means |
|---|---|---|---|
| Continuum Hypothesis (CH) | \(2^{\aleph_0}=\aleph_1\) (no set of reals with size strictly between countable and continuum) | Independent | There are models of ZFC where CH holds and models of ZFC where CH fails |

| Landmark result | Year | Mathematician | Statement (relative consistency) | Core idea (very high-level) |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| â€œCH canâ€™t be refuted from ZF(C)â€ | 1940 | GÃ¶del | If ZF is consistent, then ZF + GCH is consistent; in particular ZFC + CH is consistent | Build the **constructible universe** \(L\); show \(L\models\) GCH |
| â€œCH canâ€™t be proved from ZFCâ€ | 1963 | Cohen | If ZFC is consistent, then ZFC + Â¬CH is consistent | Invent **forcing**; add generic reals so that \(2^{\aleph_0}>\aleph_1\) (e.g., \(=\aleph_2\)) while preserving ZFC |

### What can actually be proved (and how people â€œdecideâ€ CH by adding principles)

| Theory (ZFC + â€¦) | Consequence for \(2^{\aleph_0}\) | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| \(L\) (the constructible universe) or ZFC + GCH | \(2^{\aleph_0}=\aleph_1\) (CH true) | GÃ¶delâ€™s model \(L\) satisfies GCH at every infinite cardinal |
| Proper Forcing Axiom (PFA) | \(2^{\aleph_0}=\aleph_2\) (CH false) | A widely studied strengthening of Martinâ€™s Axiom; implies many strong structural regularities |
| â€œEaston patternsâ€ on regular cardinals | Very flexible continuum function | Eastonâ€™s theorem shows that, subject to monotonicity/cofinality constraints, \(2^\kappa\) for regular \(\kappa\) can be forced to many assigned values; in particular the continuum can be made \(\aleph_2, \aleph_3,\dots\) |

### Ultra-brief intuition sketches (no heavy formalism)

| Sketch | Idea in one paragraph |
|---|---|
| GÃ¶delâ€™s \(L\) | Define a canonical inner model \(L\) by building sets in a highly disciplined, stage-by-stage way. Because \(L\) contains only â€œdefinableâ€ sets, cardinal arithmetic there is very tightly controlled; one proves in \(L\) that \(2^\kappa=\kappa^+\) for every infinite \(\kappa\), hence CH holds in \(L\). Since \(L\) satisfies all ZFC axioms, ZFC canâ€™t refute CH. |
| Cohenâ€™s forcing | Start with a transitive model \(M\models\)ZFC. Choose a partial order \(\mathbb P\) that â€œadds new realsâ€ but doesnâ€™t collapse cardinals (e.g., ccc forcing). Extend \(M\) to a larger model \(M[G]\) by adjoining a **generic filter** \(G\subseteq\mathbb P\). In \(M[G]\), the number of reals increases to, say, \(\aleph_2\), so \(2^{\aleph_0}=\aleph_2\) and CH fails. Because ZFC still holds in \(M[G]\), ZFC canâ€™t prove CH. |

