Weâ€™ll work with Option A, focusing on the linearized Boltzmann around Maxwellian. The structure will include a table with definitions, assumptions, the statement, proof sketch, checks, gaps, and next steps, avoiding bullet points. The entropy stability lemma will be presented using an operator L and hypocoercivity, defining spaces and a spectral gap efficiently.
Iâ€™m setting up the hypocoercivity argument using a modified energy \( H_\epsilon(f) = ||f||^2 + \alpha \langle Af, f \rangle \), where \( A \) is selected between transport and collision operators. We aim to show that \( \frac{d}{dt} H \leq -\mu H \) for small Knudsen scaling, applying this to the linearized Boltzmann equation with periodic boundary conditions. The resulting lemma defines coercivity for hard-sphere collision kernels and hypocoercivity for the full operator.
We will show exponential decay of the modified entropy \( E(f) = ||f||^2 + a \langle \nabla_x \cdot \nabla_v f, f \rangle + b ||\nabla_x f||^2 \), with constants \( c \) and \( \mu > 0 \) for solutions with zero macroscopic mean. This approach aligns with hypocoercivity results from Villani and others. Weâ€™ll present definitions, assumptions, and the claim in table format, discussing entropy production and the interplay with relative entropy.
Iâ€™ll introduce the micro-macro decomposition to describe the projection onto the nullspace, using \( P f = \{ a(x) + b(x) \cdot v + c(x)(|v|^2 - d) \} M^{1/2} \) and norms with derivatives. The energy functional \( E[f] = ||f||^2 + \alpha\langle \nabla_x f, \nabla_v f \rangle \) quantifies the behavior in Hilbert space. Then, Iâ€™ll compute the derivative and bound it by \( -\kappa E \), using the linearized Boltzmann equation.

