Iâ€™m calculating the sum of all components of âŸ¨S, SâŸ©_M, which simplifies to (2/3) * r^4. Since r^2 follows a chi-square distribution, I compute E[r^4] in terms of its variance and mean squared. This lets me evaluate the expectation needed based on the normal distribution in 3D with variance 1.
For the chi-square distribution with \( k = 3 \), the expectation \( E[r^4] = 15 \), giving us \( \langle S, S \rangle_M = 10 \). Next, the term \( -\langle L S, S \rangle_M \) for hard spheres with a cutoff is related to the shear mode collisional frequency. The result involves the collision kernel and can be parameterized.
