I'm examining the linearization process. For the heat semigroup on the torus, the second derivative yields a factor of \((Î½ s)^{-1}\), impacting the \(L^2\) norm. To avoid divergence, I shift from \(L^2\) to \(H^1\), which improves one derivative per heat semigroup step. I'll integrate this carefully, with attention to singularities.
If \( f \in H^1 \), then we get some nice estimates:
\[
\| \nabla^2 e^{t\Delta} f \| \leq C t^{-1/2} \| \nabla f \| 
\]
This avoids divergence and includes scaling with \( \nu \). Then, for the convective term, I estimate using \( \| u \|_{L^3} \| \nabla u \|_{L^6} \) or a block-level bound using Gronwall with small \( \sup H^1 \). Iâ€™ll finish with the final bounds involving mixing time.
To bound \( Xi_n \), I combine terms: 
\[
Xi_n \leq C1 \tau_{mix} U_n + C2 \nu^{-1/2} \tau_{mix}^{1/2} U_n^{1/2} + \text{small nonlinear term}.
\]
To ensure the form fits, I address the \( U_n^{1/2} \) and use blockwise decay in \( H^1 \). Iâ€™ll constrain \( U_n \) using smallness thresholds and compute constants. Finally, I define \( U_n = \| u(t_n) \|_{H^1}^2 \).

