### **Angular Splitting Lemma (Skeleton Form)**  

| Component | Statement |
|-----------|-----------|
| **Setup** | For the Boltzmann collision kernel \( B(|v-v_*|,\cos\theta) = |v-v_*|^\gamma b(\cos\theta)\), assume non-cutoff: \( b(\cos\theta) \sim \theta^{-1-2s}, \, 0<s<1\). |
| **Splitting** | Fix a small angle cutoff \( \theta_0 \). Then split the operator into two regimes: <br> â€¢ **Grazing (singular)**: \( 0 < \theta < \theta_0\). <br> â€¢ **Non-grazing (regular)**: \( \theta_0 < \theta \leq \pi/2\). |
| **Result** | \( Q(f,f) = Q^{\text{graze}}_{\theta<\theta_0}(f,f) + Q^{\text{reg}}_{\theta>\theta_0}(f,f). \) <br> Moreover: <br> â€¢ \(Q^{\text{reg}}\) is bounded and smooth (acts like a cutoff operator). <br> â€¢ \(Q^{\text{graze}}\) carries the non-integrable singularity and will generate the fractional Laplacian + log correction in Fourier space. |
| **Skeleton Inequality** | \(\displaystyle \langle Q^{\text{graze}}(f,f), f \rangle \;\sim\; \int_{|\xi|} |\hat f(\xi)|^2 \, |\xi|^{2s} \, \log(1+|\xi|)\, d\xi \quad + \; \text{error bounded by } Q^{\text{reg}}.\) |

---

âš“ **Anchor insight:**  
This lemma **isolates the bad grazing part** into a form thatâ€™s tailor-made for Fourier symbol extraction (Step S3 later). The â€œgoodâ€ part is harmless and can be absorbed into the Lyapunov functional.  

---

ðŸ‘‰ Shall I now **flesh out the actual skeleton proof of this Angular Splitting Lemma** (i.e. write the steps showing why grazing vs non-grazing behave this way), so we lock S1 into place before moving to S2 (Cancellation)?

## USER
Yes. 

## ASSISTANT
Perfect. Letâ€™s **lock in S1** with a clean skeleton proof.  

---

## **Skeleton Proof â€“ Angular Splitting Lemma (S1)**  

| Step | Idea | Statement |
|------|------|-----------|
| 1 | **Write kernel** | \(B(|v-v_*|,\cos\theta) = |v-v_*|^\gamma \, b(\cos\theta),\) with \( b(\cos\theta) \sim \theta^{-1-2s}\). |
| 2 | **Split angular domain** | Fix \(0<\theta_0\ll 1\). Define: <br> â€¢ Grazing part: \( b_{\text{graze}}(\theta) = b(\theta)\chi_{\theta<\theta_0}\). <br> â€¢ Regular part: \( b_{\text{reg}}(\theta) = b(\theta)\chi_{\theta>\theta_0}\). |
| 3 | **Decompose operator** | \( Q(f,f) = Q^{\text{graze}}(f,f) + Q^{\text{reg}}(f,f).\) |
| 4 | **Bound regular part** | Since \( b_{\text{reg}}(\theta)\in L^1\), the kernel is integrable. Then: <br> \( \|Q^{\text{reg}}(f,f)\|_{L^2} \lesssim \|f\|_{L^2}\|f\|_{L^1_{\gamma+}}.\) <br> So \(Q^{\text{reg}}\) is controlled like cutoff Boltzmann. |
| 5 | **Analyze grazing part** | For \(0<\theta<\theta_0\), use Carleman/Fourier representation: <br> \(\displaystyle \langle Q^{\text{graze}}(f,f), f\rangle = \int_{\mathbb R^d} \Psi(\xi) |\hat f(\xi)|^2 \, d\xi,\) with symbol \(\Psi(\xi) \sim |\xi|^{2s} \log(1+|\xi|).\) |
| 6 | **Conclusion** | \(Q^{\text{graze}}\) carries the singular structure (fractional Laplacian + log), while \(Q^{\text{reg}}\) is bounded. Together: <br> \(\langle Q(f,f),f\rangle \approx \int |\hat f(\xi)|^2 \, (|\xi|^{2s}\log(1+|\xi|)+O(1)) \, d\xi.\) |

---

âœ… **Result:** The operator has been cleanly split: one part integrable & harmless, one part carrying the rough â€œfractional + logâ€ structure.  

